{"id": 232003330, "title": "TAIT: Hugh Campbell imbued the Elks, and Edmonton, with his championship style", "text": "\u201cIt\u2019s my coaching style. I really encourage my players to play for one another and be good friends,\u201d he said. Campbell took his philosophy of creating a culture of caring with him when he became Elks GM \u2014 from 1986 to 1997 \u2014 and then as president and CEO \u2014 1998-2006 \u2014 when he retired: the second year in a row the Elks didn\u2019t make the CFL playoffs after their historic romp. Campbell looked around the room. Every man sitting at tables was enjoying chatting with other alumni. \u201cEveryone of those guys are friends \u2014 and I\u2019m proud of that,\u201d Campbell said. \u201cThey stay in touch with one another and email each other all the time.\u201d The Elks who were Grey Cup champions gathered in the press box Saturday a few minutes before halftime. The procession was led by four RCMP members guarding the Grey Cup.", "summary": "Hugh Campbell walked down a fairly steep slope Friday afternoon on the northeast side of Commonwealth stadium. \u201cWhat a beautiful stadium. I coached the first football game here,\u201d he said. \u201cIn 1978. Right after the Commonwealth Games, We beat the B.C. Lions.\u201d Winning. It circled around the Edmonton Elks, Clarke Stadium and Commonwealth Stadium. It [&#8230;]", "url": "https://edmontonsun.com/opinion/columnists/tait-hugh-campbell-imbued-the-elks-and-edmonton-with-his-championship-style", "image": "https://smartcdn.gprod.postmedia.digital/edmontonsun/wp-content/uploads/2024/06/seanretire.jpg?quality=100&strip=all", "video": null, "publish_date": "2024-06-09 12:00:12", "author": "Cam Tait", "authors": ["Cam Tait"], "language": "en", "source_country": "ca", "sentiment": -0.139}